Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Projective Measurements", "TechNoteSection",
 CellTags->"Section21",
 CellID->1477689096,ExpressionUUID->"0bfc3d8a-85b8-4a67-b149-c8674cc3bcd1"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Postulate 3",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". A physical quantity is described by an \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]observable\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]\[LongDash]a Hermitian operator. Upon measurement of \
an observable ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["A", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a3f0c00d-d378-493a-9e18-66e31525e670"],
 ", the outcome is probabilistically selected from one of the eigenvalues ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["a", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a97c6dc4-5da6-4329-8cec-1c68901cea05"],
 " of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["A", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c30f2455-ed17-4c10-9da5-746cae2733ec"],
 ". When the system is in the state |\[Psi]\:27e9 right before measurement, \
the probability of a particular outcome ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["a", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a6412c60-3725-42ab-8fcb-ee1907b1c7cb"],
 " is given by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["P", "a"], "=", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
      TemplateBox[{"a", "\[Psi]"},
       "BraKet"], "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], "2"]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"af3bc4c3-6ccf-4052-b12f-6a9e2bd863b1"],
 ", where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{"a"},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d202b6c0-9a46-46a6-9403-6532a3fa99a9"],
 " is the eigenstate of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["A", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f2315f7e-abc8-48a4-9e60-13ec7a73fa9b"],
 " belonging to the eigenvalue ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["a", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a171e63c-89a6-44a6-a067-9fa565f7fd2d"],
 ". Right after measurement, the state \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]collapses\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] to the eigenstate ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{"a"},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f193fcab-f858-4644-9a28-7c904d906187"],
 " corresponding to outcome ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["a", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "27c28272-aa34-401a-9ce2-a466da45b1ad"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->2019742564,ExpressionUUID->"129a35fc-761e-4622-bc6c-794c40fa2a10"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The postulate points out several striking features that distinguish quantum \
mechanics from classical mechanics. First, a measurable physical quantity \
(i.e., an observable) is not described by a simple number but by an operator \
acting on the vectors that describe the quantum states of the system (see ",
 ButtonBox["Postulate 1",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/QuantumStates#866638043"],
 ")."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->539265019,ExpressionUUID->"0897f73a-2b40-4172-a269-edd175cf15ce"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Second, measurement brings about a sudden collapse of the state vector \
whereby an unavoidable disturbance by mere measurement causes obvious \
obstacles to naively examining quantum states. At the same time, this opens \
new opportunities for practical applications such as to achieve secure \
quantum communications. Furthermore, this collapse is a peculiar dynamics of \
quantum states and an alternative to that governed by the \
Schr\[ODoubleDot]dinger equation (",
 ButtonBox["Postulate 2",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/TimeEvolution#903787946"],
 "), which turns out to be useful to construct measurement-based quantum \
computing architectures. Even in the common dynamical schemes of quantum \
computation, measurement is often used to initialize the quantum registers to \
the logical basis states. Combined with classical communications, measurement \
also enriches available gate operations."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1046183993,ExpressionUUID->"56510205-02ba-4581-8628-4c24b258d6c1"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Third, the postulate makes it clear that even if the state vector |\[Psi]\
\:27e9 is known, which comprises the complete description of the state \
according to Postulate 1, one cannot infer the measurement results even in \
principle, but only the probabilities of possible outcomes. The description \
is inherently statistical, and one needs to measure an ensemble of \
identically prepared systems to extract the value of an observable in terms \
of its statistical moments such as the expectation value. Given a state \
vector |\[Psi]\:27e9, the expectation value of operator ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["A", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8a3a4d13-42a8-44c2-a8f7-20dc124a553a"],
 " is obtained by using elementary theory of probability,"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1765752362,ExpressionUUID->"b351bf5a-ef87-4f60-83f7-b2a5c81c5834"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[LeftAngleBracket]", "A", "\[RightAngleBracket]"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["\[Sum]", "a"], 
