Visible->True,
TaggingRules->{
 "ModificationHighlight" -> False, "ColorType" -> "", "LinkTrails" -> "", 
  "ExampleCounter" -> 1, 
  "Openers" -> {
   "PrimaryExamplesSection" -> Open, "ExampleSection" -> {"0" -> Open}}, 
  "NewStyles" -> True, "CitationPopupData" -> {"2021", ""}, "ShowCitation" -> 
  False, "RootCaptions" -> "", "HeaderCoreAreaLink" -> {}, 
  "Metadata" -> {
   "built" -> "{2026, 4, 12, 17, 59, 56.517781}", 
    "history" -> {"13", "", "", ""}, "context" -> "QuantumMob`Q3`", 
    "keywords" -> {
     "projective measurement", "von Neumann scheme", "no-cloning theorem"}, 
    "specialkeywords" -> {}, "tutorialcollectionlinks" -> {}, "index" -> True,
     "label" -> "Quantum Mob/ Q3 Tech Note", "language" -> "en", "paclet" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3", "status" -> "None", "summary" -> 
    "In classical mechanics, just like the state of motion, a physical \
quantity is described by a simple number for a scalar quantity or by a set of \
numbers for a vector quantity. As such, measurement merely assesses such \
number(s) and casts technological questions concerning only measuring \
devices. In quantum mechanics, measurement is totally different and is deeply \
intermingled into quantum theory itself. See also Section 1.3 of the Quantum \
Workbook (2022). Postulate 3. A physical quantity is described by an \
'observable'\\[LongDash]a Hermitian operator. Upon measurement of an \
observable A, the outcome is probabilistically selected from one of the \
eigenvalues a of A. When the system is in the state |\\[Psi]\:27e9 right \
before measurement, the probability of a particular outcome a is given by \
P_a=|TemplateBox[{a, \\[Psi]}, BraKet]|^2, where TemplateBox[{a}, Ket] is the \
eigenstate of A belonging to the eigenvalue a. Right after measurement, the \
state 'collapses' to the eigenstate TemplateBox[{a}, Ket] corresponding to \
outcome a.", "synonyms" -> {}, "tabletags" -> {}, "title" -> 
    "Measurements on Quantum States", "titlemodifier" -> "", 
    "metadescription" -> "", "windowtitle" -> 
    "Measurements on Quantum States", "type" -> "Tech Note", "uri" -> 
    "QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/MeasurementsOnQuantumStates"}},
